column2: i walked into her hospital room. tubes everywhere & machines buzzing to keep her alive. it hit my like a ton of bricks. my heart sank as i thought about all the anger i was holding toward her & the self righteous judgements i had placed on her for being an addict. she was human & flawed just like me. it was in that moment that i realized i wasn't any better.

column1: when i was a teenager i suffered from an eating disorder & self harm behaviors. at 12 yrs old i was hospitalized for a suicide attempt. years of therapy & a lot of self love work & i was finally able to overcome it.
and as i stood there looking at my little sister
column2: i saw myself in her. i wasn't any better. she was struggling with mental illness & a lack of self love the same way i had. drugs & the addiction were how her's manifested
column3: but at the root our issues were very much the same.

column1: for 5 days i begged & prayed that she would forgive me
column2: but she never woke up. she took her final breath on march 2nd

column1: loosing my sister changed the way i view the world. it helped me to realize that we're all a lot more the same than we are different. we all have highs & lows & darkness & light. that's the essence of being human.
while i would give anything to have her back & be a better sister
column2: i cannot change the past. all i can do is honor her memory by sharing her story & spreading compassion & love. it's my mission in life to inspire & empower women (and men) to love themselves. because when we love ourselves & are healthy
column4: eating disorders & suicide attempts are minimized & families don't have to go through this pain.

column1: if you're struggling with any of these things
column2: i hope that you know you aren't alone. i hope you talk to the people you love & professionals & get the help you need to find your way out of the darkness. there is so much goodness & light waiting on the other side. i'm sending you so much love right now. ğŸ’› i see you. i love you.

column1: please share this post with anyone you think could be fit from knowing they aren't alone. let's #endthestigma

column1: recy taylor chose not to stay silent during a time
column2: living in the jim crow south
column4: where her truth could have gotten her killed. a mother and wife of one

column6: she was forced into a car at gunpoint by a group of seven white men
column7: taken into the forest and raped by six of them. she could have remained quiet
column9: nothing would be done by abbeville police to bring her justice. and yet
column10: she reported her attackers to police. despite the men not denying the crime
column11: and there being witnesses to the kidnapping
column12: her attackers were not arrested. they were never held accountable for their actions
column14: who sent a one rosa parks to abbeville to investigate the case and take the story nationally. she received support from a number of big names
column15: including web dubois and langston hughes.

column2: her house was firebombed. she was falsely labeled as a prostitute. her family couldn't go out at night. she inevitably left for florida and found work picking oranges. she and her husband later separated
column3: and their only child died in 1967. a woman who went through so much
column5: undeservedly. when asked what she wanted so many years later
column6: she simply said in 2010 that she wanted someone to say they were sorry for doing nothing about the injustice she faced. ""it would mean a whole lot to me
column7: â€ she said. â€œthe people who done this to me â€¦ they canâ€™t do no apologizing. most of them is gone.""

column2: taylor finally received that apology -- from the alabama legislature. she also received a doc on her life in 2017
column4: in ""the rape of recy taylor."" it would ensure her voice

column1: 26428;instagram;2019-02-26 13:33:45;FALSE;"according to the national sexual violence resource center * 1 in 5 women and 1 in 71 men will be raped at some point in their lives.
* in the united stares 1 in 3 women and 1 in 6 men experienced some form of contact sexual violence in their lifetime.
* 51.1% of female victims of rape reported being raped by an intimate partner and 40.8% by an acquaintance.
* 52.4% of male victims report being raped by an acquaintance and 15.1% by a stranger.
* 49.5% of multiracial women and over 45% of american indian/alaska native women were subjected to some form of contact sexual violence in their lifetime.
* 91% of victims of rape and sexual assault are female
column2: and 9% are male * in 8 out of 10 cases of rape

column1: * 8% of rapes occur while the victim is at work.
the problem of sexual violence runs rampant
column2: and yet rape is the most under-reported crime; 63% of sexual assaults are not reported to police. of the remaining 37% that are reported less than 10% are instances of false reporting. the facts are clear
column3: and still the culture that would rather #victims of sexually based crimes remain silent prevails.

column1: 26495;instagram;2019-02-26 15:09:24;FALSE;"many of you know i'm working on a project called the teddy bear campaign

it is a firestarter social impact campaign that tells the story of a school shooting from the perspective of a teddy bear. the culmination of the campaign is 535 kids delivering 535 teddy bears to the steps of the us capital commemorating the 20th anniversary of the columbine shooting.
i was explaining the campaign to a woman and she asked me: ""why do you care? did you lose someone to gun violence?"" all i could think to myself is...""is this a real question?"" i smiled
column2: then i asked the woman a couple of questions.

column1: do you want live in a world where a booty pic
column2: or sexy pic ""works"" on the algorithm and gets thousands of likes on social media and makes you famous?

column1: do you want to live in a world where if someone post a picture giving a homeless person money that person will then be labeled as an attention whore and be laughed at?!?!?!? or

do you want to live in a world where people that have a passion for change (changing themselves and changing the world) can take a stand for causes they believe in simply because they have an idea of how the world can be a better place and want to take action to do something?

i asked her finally ""which world do you want to live in?"" we are living in some of the greatest yet most challenging times of our human existence and we need more than slacktivists to change profile pics and make posts hoping shit gets better.
answering the challenges of our times is what a firestarter does.
a firestarter accepts the challenge when their backs against the wall.
a firestarter answers the challenge when destiny makes the call.
a firestarter pushes through the challenge while flexing a little muscle.
a firestarter pursues the challenge when success requires that you hustle.
in the words of the firestarter mlk
column2: let's use him to evoke all of our greatest talents.

column1: your ultimate measure is not where you stand at times of comfort and convenience but where you stand at times of controversy and challenge.
and that is how to be a firestarter!
check out the teddy bear campaign link in bio.

column2: and walked up to little adam's peak. the view was amazing and on the way down i got to try a zipline. it was so much fun! and i immediately wanted to do it 100 times more.

column1: after we got back down we decided to go shopping there and i found this shop with hundreds of wood carvings. they were spectacular and i really wanted to buy one
column2: but i didn't know which. so i started talking with the shop assistant and he told me about the different statues and the different religions that went with them. i took loads of pictures and had a blast. then he asked for a picture with me
column3: and i though ""why not"". and then
column4: right when i took the picture
column5: he grabbed my ass and then slid his hand down my leg. i felt horrible. i completely froze up and instead of telling him off i ran out of the store as fast as i could. inside i was gutted
column6: and from one act made by a stranger within less than 5 seconds. all my good feelings about the entire trip to ella suddenly just vanished and instead i felt like my insides were heavy with a feeling i can't really name. perhaps a mixture of shame and hopelessness. it was shit.

column1: i spent the entire rest of the evening trying to rid myself of all the negative feelings this brought up so that one asshole wouldn't ruin the entire trip for me
column2: but it was extremely hard. for me
column3: this was completely unacceptable and the fact that i didn't even manage to tell him off or do anything at all other than run away made me really ashamed of myself.

column1: update: i've changed my wording a bit. i wrote ""and from such a small thing"". i agree that it was not a small thing at all and i've changed my wording so what i meant is a bit clearer.";;en;#shitending

column1: 26534;instagram;2019-02-26 15:43:49;FALSE;last night i had the honor of seeing tarana burke the creator of the #metoo movement speak and it was powerful. woke up this morning reflecting on her words and it has me thinking about my own personal experiences and made me realize i came into feminism from simply just being around black women. from my mother
column3: close friends and all of the black women who nurtured me as a child growing up in the black church. we often talk about a language of liberation but never a language of healing. between whatâ€™s happening in popular culture right now and our own communities it made me realize that i...we have failed the women in our communities when it comes to sexual violence. i often think about all of the r kellyâ€™s my own community

column1: 26614;instagram;2019-02-26 17:25:12;FALSE;"today is my sons birthday. someday he will find out how hard his mother

column6: your mimi and your godmother darlene

column1: 26770;instagram;2019-02-26 19:52:24;FALSE;"*possible trigger warning* for about 10 years leading up to my 20's i was very lost. throughout those 10 years i would have bouts of time where i would attempt to turn my life into the positive one i always desired. i practiced mindfulness
column2: different healthy diets and workout regimens. in hope's to boost positivity in my life
column3: but depression always won. then i was 23. at the time i was not in the best of relationships
column5: always sad. one day i woke up and it all made sence. for the past 10 years i had been keeping something very personal hidden. this trauma was so deep that at times my anxiety would overtake me. that day i decided i was going to be open and deal with this issue head on.....

column1: when i was 13 i was sexually abused. for a month of my life i was raped every night. from there i kept that secret untill 23. i finally told my parents
column2: my friends and i finally sought help. i was in a full time counseling program
column3: to talk and work though my trama. i learned that i deserve respect and love. i learned that taking care of my mind is just as important as taking care of my body . it takes dedication
column4: consistancy and patients. ptsd wont ever go away
column5: but it gets better. surrounding myself with people who support and respect me
column6: makes it easier to heal. finding things that make my body and mind happy. i am now 29 and loving life. i'm engaged to a wonderful man and have 4 beautiful children. couldn't be happier. i take care of my mental health with proper medication and counseling. i take care of my body by eating healthy wile allowing myself to indulge every once in awile. i also discovered my favorite workouts! pilates videos on youtube . blogilates helped me lose 80lbs after pregnancy and keeps me motivated. pilates helps with my mental health and also makes me feel good about myself. finding the root cause for my problems was the start. even though it took 10 years
column7: i didnt let it break me. i transformed myself with love and support. nobody is perfect but you have the power to be the best you

column1: 26836;instagram;2019-02-26 20:53:11;FALSE;"""i taught myself to be grateful that i survived even if survival didn't look like much.

column3: to tell myself that what i went through wasn't 'that bad' allowed me to break down my trauma into something more manageable
column4: into something i could carry with me instead of allowing the magnitude of it to destroy me. .

column2: diminishing my experience hurt me far more than it helped. i created an unrealistic measure for what was acceptable in how i was treated in relationships
column4: in random encounters with strangers. that is to say that if i even had a bar for how i deserved to be treated
column5: that bar was so low it was buried far belowground. if being gang-raped wasn't that bad
column6: then it wasn't at all that bad being shoved or having my arm grabbed so hard it left five bruises in the form of fingerprints or being catcalled for having large breasts or having a hand shoved down my pants or being told i should be grateful for romantic attention because i wasn't good enough and on and on. everything was terrible but none of it was that bad.""

column2: 2009 i surrendered to the daâ€™s office in a county outside of philadelphia. i was processed and taken to the county jail. it was about 10 days after that date that i made an initial appearance in the local court as the case had not yet been transferred to the county level. i was transported to the court hearing by two detectives
column3: a male and female from the daâ€™s office
column4: i had on my jail uniform since they did not allow me to change into my personal clothing. the uniform is identical to a scrub outfit you would see a surgeon wearing
column5: except you are not allowed to choose the size and they are generally loose fitting and baggy. my bra was taken from me upon my initial arrival at the jail because it contained underwire and my family was not allowed to provide me with a replacement
column6: so i was forced to spend my time there bra-less. the detectives handcuffed me wrapped a chain around my waist to which the handcuffs were chained with another chain running down from my waist to the shackles around my ankles.

column1: upon arriving at the municipal court i was placed in a very small room a little bit bigger than a standard clothes closet
column5: concrete floor with wooden benches attached to 3 of those walls
column6: there was in the very high ceiling a low wattage light but no cameras. the door to this holding cell was solid
column7: made of heavily reinforced wood with no window. i was locked in this room with two males who were waiting to see the judge. they were both in their own clothes and only had handcuffs on. i immediately sat in the front corner of the room with my back to the wall. one of the men was taken from the room to appear before the judge
column8: the door to the cell was slammed shut and locked when the other man started to say to me
column9: â€œi want to feel your tittiesâ€ â€œjust let me feel themâ€ â€œi just want to feel those tittiesâ€ he was saying this as he was crossing the small room towards me. i screamed no

column1: 26987;instagram;2019-02-27 00:01:14;FALSE;"i'm in therapy. i have anxiety/agoraphobia so getting myself to my therapists office e is a huge deal for me. today
column2: i was able to get myself there and had a productive session. i'm only going to mention the following to spread awareness.

column1: i've been sexually abuse and sexual assaulted multiple times. my therapist switched my ptsd dx to c-ptsd due to the extensive trauma i've endured. this trauma that still follows me around after years of being separarted from most of it (my most recent attack was in september). it's hard to heal. every time i engage in art work with my therapist
column2: body memories and flashbacks flood me. it causes a lot of distress. my therapist and i decided today to look into getting me an emdr therapist to have in addition to her
column3: specifically to work on my trauma.

column1: i want to be free from those who have hurt me. i don't want to hold on to it anymore. i know the healing process will be hard af but it's necessary for me to not be as plagued by it. #metoo #sexualassaultsurvivor #sexualabusesurvivor";;en;#metoo

column1: 26989;instagram;2019-02-27 00:02:49;FALSE;"having an autoimmune disease is foreign to me. no one ever really talks about their struggles. i believe that's related to the fact that some of the symptoms are so bizarre that people might feel like they are not believable or possibly don't want to be labeled as a whiner or complainer.
i was lucky and had people in my life that saw a difference  in me and encouraged me to see a doctor. also
column2: i had my sister-in-law help me through this and she's been so encouraging and helpful. however
column3: so much of her journey was taken alone and it shouldn't have been. where's the #metoo movement on chronic health issues and mental health?

column1: i have been holding off discussing my diagnosis out of superstition as my doctors and i haven't discussed the treatment yet (that happens next week). however
